</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0001">1</a>
	
   <p>For other accounts of Cheneys resignation from the army, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-01-02-0091&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-01-02-0091-fn-0001#GEWN-03-01-02-0091-fn-0001" class="document">General Orders, 22 July 1775, n.1</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-01-02-0304" class="document">Cheney to GW, 4 Sept. 1775</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0235" class="document">GW to Trumbull, 29 Oct. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Philip Turner (17401815) of Norwich was surgeon of the 8th Connecticut Regiment. In October 1776 the Connecticut general assembly appointed Turner physician and surgeon for the states Continental troops, and in April 1777 the Continental Congress made him surgeon general of the hospital in the eastern department. He was named a hospital physician and surgeon in October 1780 and resigned from the Continental service the following June.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>The other surgeons mate in the 3d Connecticut Regiment was Elijah Adams.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>The Connecticut council of safety appointed Cheney surgeon of the 3d Connecticut Regiment on 4 Oct. (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Royal R. Hinman, comp. &lt;i&gt;A Historical Collection, from Official Records, Files &amp;amp;c., of the Part Sustained by Connecticut, during the War of the Revolution&lt;/i&gt;. Hartford, 1842. ]">Hinman, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Historical Collection</span></span>, 335).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>The enclosed extract has not been found.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>For Thomas Dyers case, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0110" class="document">General Orders, 7 Oct. 1775</a>, and for that of Ebenezer Huntington, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0048" class="document">GW to Joseph Spencer, 26 Sept. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>Moses Cleveland (Cleaveland; 17541806) of Canterbury left Yale College to join the army, became an ensign in the 2d Connecticut Regiment on 1 Jan. 1777, and was promoted to lieutenant the following December. GW appointed
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-02-02-pb-0322">[322]</span>
Cleveland a lieutenant in the corps of sappers and miners on 2 Aug. 1779 and a few weeks later advanced him to captain-lieutenant, which rank Cleveland held until he resigned in June 1781. Peter Perit (Perritt) served as a captain in Col. Charles Webbs regiment until April 1776 when GW ordered him to take command of the armed sloop <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Hester</span>. In August 1776 Perit joined Knoxs artillery regiment at Fort Washington where he was captured the following November. After his exchange in October 1778, Perit sought unsuccessfully to rejoin the army.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0292-fn-0008">8</a>

   <p>The draft is endorsed in part: Novr 7Comy Phelps here informed 53 l. sent forward some time agoabout one Ton went on yesterday.</p>

</div>
</div>
